gten.org/news/2019/12/4/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-offense-and-select-individual-honors.aspx|title=Big Ten Announces Football All-Conference Teams for Offense and Select Individual Honors|website=bigten.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Griese-Brees Quarterback of the Year]]\n|-\n|AP Big Ten Offensive Player of the Year\n|December 11, 2019\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/ohio-state-leads-pack-ap-all-big-ten-top-honors-2019-dec|title=Ohio State leads the pack in AP All-Big Ten top honors|date=2019-12-11|website=WBNS-10TV Columbus, Ohio {{!}} Columbus News, Weather & Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== All-American Players ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |NCAA Recognized All-American Honors\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Player\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Position\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |AFCA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afca.com/wisconsins-jonathan-taylor-lsus-grant-delpit-headline-2019-afca-fbs-coaches-all-america-teams/|title=AFCA Announces 2019 FBS Coaches' All-America Team|website=www.afca.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |AP<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbc4i.com/sports/buckeyes/7-buckeyes-named-to-ap-all-american-teams/|title=7 Buckeyes named to AP All-American teams|date=2019-12-16|website=NBC4 WCMH-TV|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |FWAA\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Sporting News<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-football/news/sporting-news-2019-college-football-all-americans/b3bevye8lma310clpads6xo1w|title=Sporting News 2019 college football All-Americans|website=www.sportingnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |WCFF<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Ohio-State-Buckeyes-football-Walter-Camp-All-Americans-Chase-Young-Jeffrey-Okudah-Justin-Fields-JK-Dobbins-Wyatt-Davis-140385864/|title=Five Buckeyes named Walter Camp All-Americans|website=Bucknuts|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Designation\n|-\n|[[Chase Young]]\n|DE\n|1st Team\n|1st Team\n| \n| 1st Team\n|1st Team\n| Consensus\n|-\n|[[Jeff Okudah]]\n|CB\n|1st Team\n|1st Team\n|\n|1st Team\n|1st Team\n|Consensus\n|-\n|[[Justin Fields]]\n|QB\n|2nd Team\n|2nd Team\n|\n| -\n|2nd Team\n|\n|-\n|[[J. K. Dobbins]]\n|RB/AP\n|2nd Team\n|2nd Team\n|1st Team\n|2nd Team\n|2nd Team\n|\n|-\n|[[Wyatt Davis]]\n|G\n|2nd Team\n|1st Team\n|\n|1st Team\n|2nd Team\n|\n|-\n|[[Jonah Jackson]]\n|G\n| -\n|3rd Team\n|\n| -\n| -\n|\n|-\n|[[Malik Harrison]]\n|LB\n| -\n|3rd Team\n|\n| -\n| -\n|\n|}\n<small>*The NCAA and Ohio State only recognize the AP, AFCA, FWAA, Sporting News and WCFF All-American teams to determine if a player is a Consensus or Unanimous All-American. To be named a Consensus All-American, a player must be named first team in three polls and to be Unanimous, they must be named first team in all five.</small>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Other All-American Honors\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Player\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Position\n!style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Athletic\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Athlon\n!style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Bleacher Report\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |CBS Sports\n!style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |CFN\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |ESPN\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |FOX Sports\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Phil Steele\n!style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |Scout\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |SI\n! style=\"{{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Ohio State Buckeyes|color=white|border=no}}\" |USA Today\n|-\n|[[J. K. Dobbins]]\n|RB\n| 1st\n| \n|  -\n| 1st\n|\n|  -\n|\n|\n|\n| 2nd\n| 1st\n|-\n|[[Wyatt Davis]]\n|OL\n|1st\n|\n|1st\n|1st\n|\n|1st\n|\n|\n|\n|2nd\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Chase Young]]\n|DL\n|1st\n|\n|1st\n|1st\n|\n|1st\n|\n|\n|\n|1st\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Jeff Okudah]]\n|CB\n|1st\n|\n| -\n|1st\n|\n|1st\n|\n|\n|\n|1st\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Justin Fields]]\n|QB\n| -\n|\n| -\n|2nd\n|\n| -\n|\n|\n|\n| -\n|2nd\n|-\n|[[Jordan Fuller]]\n|S\n| -\n|\n| -\n|2nd\n|\n| -\n|\n|\n|\n| -\n| -\n|}\n''See [[2019 College Football All-America Team]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ohio State Buckeyes football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019 Ohio State Buckeyes football team}}\n[[Category:2019 Big Ten Conference football season|Ohio State]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football seasons]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in Ohio|Ohio State Football]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| year = 2019\n| team = Ohio State Buckeyes\n| sport = football\n| logo = Ohio State Buckeyes logo.svg\n| logo_size = 125\n| logo_alt = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| conference = Big Ten Conference\n| division = East Division\n| short_conf = Big Ten\n| CFPRank = \n| CoachRank = 3\n| APRank = 3\n| record = 13\u20131\n| conf_record = 9\u20130\n| head_coach = [[Ryan Day (American football)|Ryan Day]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_coach = [[Kevin Wilson (American football)|Kevin Wilson]]\n| oc_year = 3rd\n| off_scheme = West Coast Spread\n| def_coach = [[Greg Mattison]]\n| dc_year = 1st\n| codef_coach1 = [[Jeff Hafley]]\n| codc1_year = 1st\n| def_scheme = [[4\u20133 defense|4\u20133]] hybrid\n| captain = Tuf Borland<br>[[J. K. Dobbins]]<br>Master Teague<br>[[K. J. Hill]]<br>C.J. Saunders<br>[[Chase Young]]\n| stadium = [[Ohio Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 102,780)\n| champion = Big Ten champion<br>Big Ten East Division champion\n| conf_champ = [[2019 Big Ten Football Championship Game|Big Ten Championship Game]]\n| conf_champ_result = W 34\u201321 vs. [[2019 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]]\n| bowl = [[2019 Fiesta Bowl (December)|Fiesta Bowl]] (CFP Semifinal) \n| bowl_result = L 23\u201329 vs. [[2019 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]]\n}}\n{{2019 Big Ten football standings}}\nThe '''2019 Ohio State Buckeyes football team''' represented [[Ohio State University]] during the [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Buckeyes played their home games at [[Ohio Stadium]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. This was the Buckeyes' 130th overall season and 107th as a member of the [[Big Ten Conference]]. They were led by [[Ryan Day (American football)|Ryan Day]], in his first season as Ohio State's full-time head coach.\n\nOhio State began the year ranked fifth in the preseason [[AP Poll]]. The Buckeyes climbed to number one in the [[College Football Playoff]] rankings by the end of the regular season, after dominating wins over [[Conference USA]] champion [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|Florida Atlantic]], [[American Athletic Conference]] runner-up [[2019 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]], and [[Mid-American Conference]] champion [[2019 Miami RedHawks football team|Miami (OH)]] in the non-conference schedule; and comfortable wins over ranked Big Ten teams [[2019 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], [[2019 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]], and [[2019 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]] in conference play. In the [[2019 Big Ten Championship Game|Big Ten Championship Game]], Ohio State defeated Wisconsin a second time, by a score of 34\u201321 to win their third consecutive conference title. In the final CFP rankings of the season, Ohio State dropped from first to second, passed by SEC champion [[2019 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]], which placed Ohio State in the [[2019 Fiesta Bowl (December)|Fiesta Bowl]] to play defending national champion and third-seeded [[2019 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]]. Ohio State lost that game, 29\u201323, to end the year at 13\u20131.\n\nThe Buckeyes were led on offense by sophomore quarterback [[Justin Fields]], an incoming transfer from [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] that was granted a waiver for immediate eligibility by the NCAA. He led the Big Ten with 3,273 passing yards and 41 passing touchdowns to go along with 10 rushing touchdowns, and finished third in voting for the [[Heisman Trophy]]. Running back [[J. K. Dobbins]] became the first Buckeye running back to eclipse the 2,000 yard mark, finishing tied atop the Big Ten with Wisconsin's [[Jonathan Taylor (American football)|Jonathan Taylor]] at 2,003 yards and 21 touchdowns. On defense, Ohio State was led by [[Chuck Bednarik Award]], [[Ted Hendricks Award]], and [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]]-winning defensive end [[Chase Young]], who led the country with 16.5 sacks and also finished in fourth in Heisman Trophy voting. He was joined on the [[2019 College Football All-America Team|first-team All-America]] by cornerback [[Jeff Okudah]]. Head coach Ryan Day was named [[Big Ten Coach of the Year]] by the media, becoming the first Ohio State head coach to win it since [[Earle Bruce]] in [[1979 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|1979]].\n\n== Previous season==\nThe [[2018 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Buckeyes]] finished the [[2018 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2018 season]] 13\u20131, 8\u20131 in [[2018 Big Ten Conference football season|Big Ten play]] to win the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|East division]]. They defeated [[2018 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]] in the [[2018 Big Ten Football Championship Game|Big Ten Championship]] 45\u201324. However, despite a 12\u20131 record, they failed to receive an invitation to the [[College Football Playoff]]. Instead, they received a bid to the [[2019 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] where they defeated [[2018 Washington Huskies football team|Washington]] 28\u201323. This was the final season for [[Urban Meyer]] as the Buckeyes' head coach, who coached at Ohio State for seven seasons. In January 2019, it was announced [[University of Georgia|Georgia]] Quarterback [[Justin Fields]] would be transferring to Ohio State.\n\n==Preseason==\n===Spring Game===\nThe 2019 Spring Game was held at Ohio Stadium on April 13, 2019, with the Gray team defeating the Scarlet team, 35\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |title=3 things learned from the Ohio State spring game |url=https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/4/13/18309275/ohio-state-spring-game-analysis-justin-fields-matthew-baldwin-garrett-wilson-jahsen-wint |website=www.landgrantholyland.com |publisher=SBNation |accessdate=13 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n! Date !! Time !! Spring Game !! Site !! TV !! Result !! Attendance\n|-\n| April 13 || 12:00 pm || Scarlet vs. Gray || [[Ohio Stadium]] \u2022 [[Columbus, OH]] || [[Big Ten Network|BTN]] || Gray 35\u201317 || 60,000\n|}\n\n===Preseason Big Ten poll===\nAlthough the Big Ten Conference has not held an official preseason poll since 2010, [[Cleveland.com]] has polled sports journalists representing all member schools as a ''de facto'' preseason media poll since 2011. For the 2019 poll, Ohio State was projected to finish in second in the East Division behind [[2019 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/07/michigan-named-big-ten-football-favorite-in-clevelandcom-2019-preseason-poll.html|title=Michigan named Big Ten football favorite in cleveland.com 2019 preseason poll|date=July 18, 2019|website=Cleveland.com|first=Doug|last=Lesmerises}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"display: inline-table;\"\n|align=\"center\" Colspan=\"3\" |'''Media poll (East Division)'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Ohio State Buckeyes|Predicted finish|Team|Votes (1st place)}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1 || Michigan || 222 (20)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2 || '''Ohio State''' || 214 (14)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 3 || Michigan State || 156\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 4 || Penn State || 154\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 5 || Indiana || 86.5\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 6 || Maryland || 82.5\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 7 || Rutgers || 37\n|}\n\n==Schedule==\nOhio State's 2019 schedule will begin with two non-conference home games, first against [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|Florida Atlantic]] of [[Conference USA]] and then against [[2019 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]] of the [[American Athletic Conference]]. Ohio State's third non-conference game, a home game against [[2019 Miami RedHawks football team|Miami (OH)]] of the [[Mid-American Conference]], will be played after the Buckeyes' conference opener against [[2019 Indiana Hoosiers football team|Indiana]].\n\nIn [[Big Ten Conference]] play, Ohio State will play all members of the East Division and draws [[2019 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]], [[2019 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]], and [[2019 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]] from the West Division.\n\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2019\n| poll = [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#AP Poll|AP Poll]] and [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#CFP Rankings|CFP Rankings]] (after November 5) released prior to game\n| timezone = Eastern\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = August 31\n| time = 12:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[2019 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|Florida Atlantic]]\n| site_stadium = [[Ohio Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus, OH]]\n| tv = [[Fox College Football|FOX]]\n| score = 45\u201321\n| attend = 103,228\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 7\n| time = 12:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[2019 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]]\n| site_stadium = Ohio Stadium\n| site_cityst = Columbus, OH\n| tv = [[ESPN College Football on ABC|ABC]]\n| score = 42\u20130\n| attend = 104,089\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 14\n| time = 12:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y \n| rank = 6\n| opponent = [[2019 Indiana Hoosiers football team|Indiana]]\n| gamename = \n| site_stadium = [[Memorial Stadium (Indiana)|Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Bloomington, Indiana|Bloomington, IN]]\n| tv = FOX\n| score = 51\u201310\n| attend = 47,945\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 21\n| time = 3:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 6\n| opponent = [[2019 Miami RedHawks football team|Miami (OH)]]\n| gamename = \n| site_stadium = Ohio Stadium\n| site_cityst = Columbus, OH\n| tv = [[Big Ten Network|BTN]]\n| score = 76\u20135\n| attend = 103,190\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 28\n| time = 7:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[2019 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]]\n| gamename = ''[[College GameDay (football TV program)|College GameDay]]''\n| site_stadium = [[Memorial Stadium (Lincoln)|Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln, NE]]\n| tv =  [[Saturday Night Football|ABC]]\n| score = 48\u20137\n| attend = 89,759\n}}\n|{{CFB 